      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Jolly Good Show  Or Was It?'' [April 8]:</p>
        <p>Though I was unaware of Stephen Fry's comments concerning the lack of discernment we Americans seem to evince in evaluating British actors, this subject has long been a source of great mirth among my set.</p>
        <p>I invite readers to sample Emma Thompson's odious multicharacter turn in ''Angels in America'' or Anthony Hopkins in, well, anything, to get a sense of just how awful (and thus fabulously entertaining) bad British acting can be. Even the truly talented deliver the occasional stinker; witness Derek Jacobi in ''Dead Again'' (directed by that celebrated canned ham, Kenneth Branagh).</p>
        <p>That these examples were lauded here perhaps speaks to our general sense that we will always be somewhat déclassé. I definitely think Mr. Fry is on to something.</p>
        <p>Glenn Baldwin  Chicago</p>
        <p>ACCENTS AND ACTING</p>
      </block>
